  "doc_id": "23486",
  "text": "Terminal telomeres are highly conserved repetitive DNA sequences found at the end of eukaryote chromosomes. They maintain chromosome integrity, but shorten with cell division. Their length predicts survival across taxa and thus indicates long-term somatic state [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Evidence for parental age to affect offspring telomere length mainly comes from humans, in which, interestingly, older fathers pass longer, rather than shorter, telomeres to their offspring [CITATION_3] . This sex-specific positive correlation between parental age and offspring telomere length, however, does not seem to be general across species (table 1) .",
